<promed@promedmail.org>
[Criticisms of USDA's BSE surveillance are included in a detailed letter
sent on 25 Jul 2005 by the Consumers Union (signed by Michael Hansen,
Ph.D., Senior Scientist and Jean Halloran, Director Food Policy
Initiatives) to Agriculture Secretary Mike Johanns; see
<http://www.yubanet.com/artman/publish/article_23199.shtml>. Among other
things, the writers indicate the need for testing of all older dairy cows
and fuller implementation of the existing requirement to test
rabies-suspected cows which were found negative to rabies. The letter is
partially based upon the comments included in the Audit Report No.
50601-9-KC, of August 2004, of The Office of Inspector General (OIG),
dealing with the 1st phase of USDA's BSE Surveillance Program; see
<http://www.usda.gov/oig/webdocs/50601-9-final.pdf>. Interested readers may
also refer to the following key documents pertaining to
USA'a BSE policy:
1. United States General Accounting Office (GAO) Report to Congressional
Requesters: Mad cow disease, Improvements in the Animal Feed Ban and Other
Regulatory Areas Would Strengthen U.S. Prevention Efforts; GAO-02-183,
January 2002
<http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d02183.pdf>
2. (APHIS) Report on measures relating to BSE in the US, prepared by an
International Subcommittee; 2 Feb 2004.
<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/lpa/issues/bse/US_BSE_Report.pdf>;
see also ref 20040205.0426. - Mod.AS]
