Date: Thu 28 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Japan Consumer Press online, 6 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://www.jcpress.com/En/Latest%20News/200507/20060706BSE%20infection%20route%20of%20Japan.htm>

Specialists demand cause investigation by fodder industry
---------------------------------------------------
The "Stock Raising System Society," composed of livestock industry
specialists, the enterprise [?], the administration, and citizens opened
the symposium "BSE and the fodder problem" at the Nippon Veterinary and
Zootechnical College on 11 Jun 2005.
Katsunosuke Mitani, Professor of Hiroshima University Graduate School,
Chairman of this society, reported on the route of infection of mad cow
disease, or bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), in cows that were born
in Japan between 1995 and 1996. "The milk replacer/milk substitute that
used animal oil and fat from the Netherlands [contaminated] by the
anomalous prion protein for the raw material might be a cause".
Prof. Mitani criticized the report of the "BSE Epidemiology Examination
Team" of the Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry that denied the milk
substitute infection theory [for its faulty] statistical work.
On the other hand, Prof. Mitani emphasized, "The fodder industry had to
share the information with consumers and to investigate the cause of BSE
infection".
Prof. Mitani points out, "The cause of BSE infection in Japan must have
been an imported raw material in the fodder used when the cows first
infected were calves" [as outlined in the] thesis, "Problem of BSE report
and in the future" presented on that day.
[Mitani went on to explain], "The first [group of cows with] mad cow
disease, or bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), was processed between
1999 and 2001. The possibility that those cows polluted the domestic
production raw material for the first time cannot be denied".
As for the milk substitute that had been given to the first infection
group, powdered oils and fats from the Netherlands were used as the raw
material.
The thesis was published in "Stock raising system society report" (No.29)
in June 2005.
--
